romHEX14 cloud API -- reference server
======================================

This directory contains the server side of the optional cloud features
in romHEX14.  The client (src/cloud/CloudClient.cpp) talks to a small
JSON / multipart API; everything in this folder is a working
implementation of that API, minus the actual ROM analysis logic --
which is intentionally a stub.

Why a stub?  The wire protocol, the auth, the rate limits, the upload
storage, the systemd unit, the nginx config -- none of those carry any
real value as a secret.  They are there because every cloud service
needs them, and shipping a known-good copy means users can spin up
their own backend in an afternoon instead of guessing.  The DTC parser
and the feature catalog, on the other hand, represent years of work
and are usually proprietary.  So we publish the harness and leave the
"interesting" part to whoever runs the server.  Plug your own engine
into engine/__init__.py and you get a working API; ship the binary
without an engine and the API answers 503 to everything except /health.

What this is, and what it is not
--------------------------------

This is the public-facing service the rx14 client posts ROMs to.  It
validates the upload, applies rate limits, optionally checks a Bearer
token, persists the bytes for offline review, and delegates to an
engine module.  It does not include any DTC trigger tables, feature
patch sets, or ECU-specific glue.  Those live in your engine module
and are the part that makes the service actually do something useful.

If you just want to verify that the rx14 client and your server can
talk to each other -- before you have a real engine -- copy
engine/example_canned.py over engine/__init__.py.  That returns a
fixed list of three DTCs and two features, marks the ROM with a small
header on disable/apply, and is enough to walk through the UI flows
end to end.

Wire protocol
-------------

GET /v1/health
    Returns {"ok": true, "service": "cloudfx", "ts": <unix>,
             "engine": "ready" | "absent"}.  No auth, no rate limit;
    the rx14 client uses it to verify configuration.

POST /v1/dtc/analyze    multipart: rom (required), family (optional)
    Returns the ECU summary and per-DTC list.  See engine/__init__.py
    for the full response shape.  IP rate-limited (default 30/h).

POST /v1/dtc/disable    multipart: rom, codes (comma-separated), family
    Returns the patched ROM as application/octet-stream.  Same rate
    bucket as analyze.  Codes can be OBD-II ("P0420"), manufacturer
    decimal ("16804"), or whatever your engine emits in analyze; the
    server passes them through verbatim.

POST /v1/features/detect    Bearer + multipart: rom, family
    Returns the feature catalog applicable to this ROM.  Bearer token
    required; see Tokens below.  Per-token rate limit (default 30/min).

POST /v1/features/apply     Bearer + multipart: rom, features, family
    Returns the patched ROM as application/octet-stream.

The family hint comes from the rx14 client's Project Properties
("Producer" dropdown) and is normalized to upper-case.  Treat it as
advisory -- if your auto-detect disagrees, prefer your own answer and
surface the mismatch in the response payload.

All error paths return {"ok": false, "error": "...", ...} with an
HTTP status that matches the failure class: 400 for malformed input,
401 for missing or wrong token, 422 for a valid request the engine
refuses to satisfy, 429 for rate limiting, 503 when the engine module
is missing on the server.

Tokens
------

Free-tier endpoints (/v1/dtc/*) need no authentication.  Pro-tier
endpoints (/v1/features/*) require a Bearer token in the Authorization
header.  Tokens are stored as SHA-256 hashes in /etc/cloudfx/tokens.json
so a leaked file alone does not authorize anything; an attacker would
need the original 32-byte secret.  The included tokens.py CLI manages
the file:

    sudo python3 tokens.py add my-laptop
    sudo python3 tokens.py list
    sudo python3 tokens.py revoke my-laptop

The raw token is printed once, on add; if you lose it, revoke and
issue a new one.  The token file is reread on every request, so
add/revoke take effect without restarting the service.

Running it locally
------------------

    cd server
    python3 -m venv venv
    . venv/bin/activate          # on Windows: venv\Scripts\activate
    pip install -r requirements.txt
    flask --app app run --port 5095 --debug

Health check from another shell:

    curl http://127.0.0.1:5095/v1/health

Without an engine you'll see {"ok": true, "engine": "absent"} -- that
is correct.  The DTC and features endpoints return 503 with a hint
pointing at engine/__init__.py.  Drop the canned example into place
to make them respond:

    cp engine/example_canned.py engine/__init__.py.canned
    # edit engine/__init__.py: import CannedEngine, alias as Engine

For the rx14 client to use your local server, open Cloud Tools ->
Configure and set the URL to http://127.0.0.1:5095 (no token needed
for the DTC tab).

Production deployment
---------------------

The recommended layout is the same one we run in our own deployment:

    /var/www/cloudfx/                 service code (this folder)
    /var/www/cloudfx/venv/            python virtualenv
    /var/www/cloudfx/engine/          your real engine implementation
    /var/lib/cloudfx/uploads/         ROMs land here, owned by service user
    /etc/cloudfx/tokens.json          0600, owned by service user

Create a service user and the directories:

    adduser --system --group --home /var/www/cloudfx cloudfx
    mkdir -p /var/lib/cloudfx/uploads /etc/cloudfx
    chown -R cloudfx:cloudfx /var/www/cloudfx /var/lib/cloudfx /etc/cloudfx
    chmod 700 /etc/cloudfx

Install the systemd unit and enable it:

    cp cloudfx.service /etc/systemd/system/
    systemctl daemon-reload
    systemctl enable --now cloudfx

The unit binds to 127.0.0.1:5095 -- it should never be exposed
directly.  Put nginx in front of it for TLS and routing:

    cp nginx.example.conf /etc/nginx/sites-available/cloudfx
    # edit server_name and certificate paths to match your domain
    ln -s ../sites-available/cloudfx /etc/nginx/sites-enabled/cloudfx
    nginx -t && systemctl reload nginx

certbot --nginx will produce the certificate paths nginx.example.conf
expects.

Configuration knobs
-------------------

The defaults in app.py are reasonable starting points; tweak via
environment variables on the systemd unit (Environment=KEY=VALUE).

    RX14_UPLOAD_ROOT       where ROMs are written.  Default
                           /var/lib/cloudfx/uploads.
    RX14_TOKENS_FILE       Pro-tier token store.  Default
                           /etc/cloudfx/tokens.json.
    RX14_MAX_UPLOAD_BYTES  ceiling on a single ROM.  Default 16 MiB;
                           keep nginx client_max_body_size above this.

Rate limit thresholds and ROM extension allow-list are constants near
the top of app.py.  The buckets are in-memory, so they reset whenever
gunicorn reloads -- fine for the volumes we see, but swap for redis
if you scale beyond one host.

Storage and privacy
-------------------

Every ROM that reaches the engine is persisted under UPLOAD_ROOT with
a deterministic, opaque filename: timestamp + sha256 prefix + 4 bytes
of randomness.  The user-supplied filename is recorded only in a
sidecar JSON, never as part of the path on disk.  This rules out both
filename-collision and path-traversal attacks in one stroke.  If you
do not need an upload archive (legal, retention, support replays...),
just empty UPLOAD_ROOT on a cron and nothing breaks; only the meta
JSONs are linked in any way to a request.

The sidecar JSON contains the SHA, the request kind (dtc.analyze,
features.apply, ...), the family hint, the original filename, the
client IP, and -- for Pro requests -- the token label that authorized
the call.  Keep an eye on the directory if you take privacy seriously;
a 16 MB ROM uploaded thirty times an hour adds up faster than you'd
think.

Implementing the engine
-----------------------

engine/__init__.py is the contract.  Replace the placeholder Engine
class with one that does real work.  Method signatures and expected
return shapes are documented inline in that file, with examples.

A few things to keep in mind.  app.py calls engine methods on the
Flask request thread; if a single call would take more than a few
seconds, queue the work yourself and return a fid the client can poll
later -- but the rx14 client today expects synchronous responses, so
you will need to update both ends to do that cleanly.

The engine sees the raw ROM bytes only; it does not see the upload
filename or any other request metadata.  If you need extra inputs,
extend the multipart contract on both ends.  Keep the response
shapes documented in __init__.py exactly the way they are -- the
rx14 client parses them by key name.

If you want the server to advertise itself differently, change the
"service" string in /v1/health.  The rx14 client doesn't care what it
returns as long as the response is JSON and the server is reachable.

